<TEXT>
us efforts to extradite suspected criminals 
hiding in other countries frequently fail in large part because the 
suspects cant be found or other nations are reluctant to arrest 
them officials say 
federal officials last year requested the return of 253 citizens 
and foreigners wanted in the united states for crimes ranging from 
drug trafficking to money laundering according to the state 
department 
only 73 were forced back 
it takes time to get these people a state department 
official said wednesday also when we ask for someone to be 
arrested that doesnt mean they can always be found 
the justice department issued a mostwanted list tuesday for a 
dozen colombian men charged with drugrelated crimes in the united 
states but bringing such suspects to american soil for trial is 
rare 
in most cases the fugitives cant be found that certainly is 
the case in colombia said the state department official who 
following department rules spoke on the condition of not being 
further identified 
the situation in colombia is further complicated by the 
reluctance of judges and magistrates there to anger the nations 
powerful drug cartels which have assassinated hundreds of jurists 
and politicians who dared to oppose them 
the latest such incident occurred last week with the murder of 
presidential candidate luis carlos galan who had promised a 
government crackdown on drug traffickers 
the only notable extradition from colombia came in 1987 when 
cocaine smuggling kingpin carlos lehder was arrested in colombia and 
brought to the united states within hours lehder charged with 
conspiring to import 33 tons of cocaine into the united states was 
sentenced to life imprisonment here 
another colombian juan ramon matta was nabbed in honduras by 
us officials in 1988 and whisked out of the country to the united 
states but that action prompted violent antiamerican 
demonstrations because honduras did not have an extradition treaty 
with the united states 
matta is jailed on drug charges in connection with the 1985 
torturemurder in mexico of us drug enforcement administration 
agent enrique camarena salazar 
despite those successes the state department official said 
extradition remains a complex and expensive procedure 
the process starts with formal charges against a person who is 
overseas the case then goes to the justice department which asks 
the state department to request that the host country arrest the 
suspect 
local authorities normally must decide whether to make the arrest 
and whether to permit the person to be deported 
the state department official said there is no master list 
breaking down the types of crimes those on the us extradition list 
face in the united states 
its not like a 10mostwanted list said justice department 
spokesman joe krovisky we go after them as the requests come in 
krovisky said the justice department normally will not identify 
the people it seeks abroad saying that information is not 
released until the person is returned to the united states or the 
