<TEXT>
todays teenagers may become tomorrows aids 
victims unless they learn the rules of safe sex say researchers who 
found that teens primarily use condoms for reasons other than 
preventing disease 
in a study of 506 youths researchers at the university of 
californias san francisco campus found that teenagers largely use 
condoms to allow easy and spontaneous sex 
among male adolescents as was found with female adolescents the 
intention to use condoms in the next year was not associated with 
believing that condoms prevent stds sexually transmitted diseases 
or that condoms are effective in preventing pregnancy the authors 
wrote 
the researchers said the results show that although sexually 
transmitted diseases other than aids are rampant among teens most 
youths think they are immune 
the findings come amidst a push by health professionals to curb 
the disease rate as well as teen pregnancies by encouraging condom 
use and indicate the approach should be geared more toward concerns 
expressed by youths in the study susan kegeles the leading 
researcher said wednesday 
she said health professionals are concerned that the same type of 
sexual behavior that leads to diseases like gonorrhea and syphilis 
frequent sex with multiple partners is putting teens at risk for 
developing acquired immune deficiency syndrome 
we know right now that 20 percent of people who have aids are 
in their twenties and since the disease usually isnt diagnosed 
until years after exposure most of those people in their twenties 
probably contracted it when they were teenagers said ms 
kegeles a research psychologist at the center for aids prevention 
studies at the san francisco campus 
health factors such as aids prevention are the most emphasized 
issue in trying to get teens to use condoms ms kegeles said 
but what we found was that although they knew that condoms 
prevent disease that wasnt connected with their intent to use 
them she said 
the study published in the august issue of the chicagobased 
american journal of diseases of children is based on surveys of 
youths who attended two health clinics in the san francisco area 
from february 1984 to september 1985 
the mean age was about 16 for girls and boys thirtytwo percent 
of the girls and 43 percent of the boys were virgins of those who 
were sexually active 59 percent of the girls and 63 percent of the 
boys had used condoms 
teens were asked if they were going to have sex in the next year 
and what factors would be involved in their decision to use condoms 
though other forms of birth control were not addressed in the 
condom survey the factors cited by teens would relate to a choice 
of condoms over three other forms of contraception the diaphragm 
birthcontrol pills or withdrawal 
ease of use enabling one to have sex on the spur of the 
moment and popularity with peers were among factors listed by both 
sexes 
