<TEXT>
rd laing the british psychiatrist who became a 
counterculture hero of the 1960s with his controversial attacks on 
the nuclear family died while vacationing in france his son said 
today he was 61 
the scottishborn psychiatrist collapsed on a tennis court 
wednesday in the southern french city of st tropez said his son 
adrian he said he did not know the cause of death its a 
shock he said in an interview 
the fire department in st tropez where laing died said the 
cause of death was believed to be heart failure 
an unorthodox pioneer in the treatment of schizophrenics ronald 
david laing jarred traditional psychiatry with his first book the 
divided self an existential study in sanity and madness 
published in 1960 
he rejected notions that schizophrenia is a genetic or biological 
aberration believing instead in the familys role in creating the 
disease although he later became more open to physiological 
theories said his son 
laings views on the strains the nuclear family could put on an 
individuals sanity fell in with the rebellious spirit of the 1960s 
counterculture which made him one of its gurus 
contending that most psychiatry added to patient misery he 
refused to treat them with drugs or electric shocks unless they 
asked for them 
sanity madness and the family written with aa esterson 
and published in 1964 presented case histories based on his 
approach to families 
the politics of experiencethe bird of paradise published 
in 1967 explored the illnesses of society presenting the insane 
the criminal and the revolutionary as mystical explorers in a 
vicious and mechanized world the times of london said 
at kingsley hall the london residential treatment hostel he 
helped to run he experimented with the therapeutic use of mescaline 
and lsd he was a prominent campaigner for the legalization of 
marijuana 
in 1964 he founded the philadelphia association a network of 
households to house the mentally distressed without giving them 
conventional treatment 
although laings work antagonized many conventional 
psychiatrists he was moured as an innovative contributor to modern 
psychiatry 
he made individual contributions to new and constructive 
thinking about the care of psychiatric patients said a statement 
from the royal college of psychiatrists 
the fontana companion to modern thought recognized the continuing 
impact of laings ideas on orthodox british psychiatry as 
witnessed by the greater attention now paid to the dynamics of a 
family one of whose members is disturbed 
born oct7 1927 and raised in a glasgow tenement block laing 
received his doctorate at glasgow university and served with a 
psychiatric unit in the army before going on to study psychoanalysis 
at the tavistock institute in london 
in the 1970s having gained international renown he became 
interested in zen buddhism wrote poems and published transcripts 
of conversations between himself and his children in the us 
magazine harpers 
he is survived by his commonlaw wife margarita an infant son 
by her his first wife anne and their daughters caron and fiona 
and sons paul and adrian said adrian laing 
fiona his first daughter spent years in mental institutions and 
was treated for schizophrenia according to adrian 31 who said he 
is writing a book on the influence of this on his fathers work his 
survivors also include two sons from a second marriage adam and 
max and a daughter natasha as well as a child benjamin by another 
commonlaw wife said adrian 
he was an antiestablishment character but wasnt an 
antipsychiatrist according to adrian who said he had studied 
his fathers works and accompanied his father to conferences 
he wanted to listen more to what people were saying to look at 
schizophrenic minds from their point of view he said his idea 
was just to let them go crazy just let them go on with it 
he said youve got to understand the politics of the family 
laings other writings included reason and violence the 
politics of experience and his 1985 account of the first 30 years 
of his life the making of a psychiatrist 
