<TEXT>
writer and artist feliks topolski who painted 
royalty as well as battle scenes for the british government died 
thursday at the age of 82 
topolski who lived in london had been suffering from heart 
trouble and diabetes said his son daniel 
topolski decided to settle in britain when he first came to 
london in 1935 to cover the jubilee celebrations of king george v 
for a polish satirical newspaper 
he was made a member of londons royal academy in recognition of 
his work which included the 100footlong painting of the 
coronation of queen elizabeth ii for buckingham palace and the 
60foot by 20foot cavalcade of the commonwealth painted for the 
1951 festival of britain 
as an official war artist for the british government from 
194045 topolski painted the battle of britain and other scenes 
drawings watercolors and oil paintings by topolski are owned by 
the british museum the tate gallery and galleries in new york 
toronto tel aviv melbourne and warsaw 
topolski also designed theatrical sets and costumes and published 
his annual personal pictorial journal chronicle from 1953 to 1979 
he was educated at the mikolaj rey school and the academy of art 
in warsaw and went to the polish officers school of artillery 
reserve 
