delays in the soviet mars program 
following the first public scrutiny of the space programs budget 
could affect us plans to launch a spacecraft to mars in 1992 a 
nasa scientist said thursday 
a leading soviet space official said that soviet plans to explore 
mars and ultimately send a manned mission there are being delayed by 
pressure to divert money to social programs 
the us program had been tentatively planned to mesh with the 
soviet program with us launches scheduled for 1992 and 1996 and 
soviet launches in 1994 and 1998 said john casani assistant 
director for flight projects at nasas jet propulsion laboratory 
that plan is now uncertain because soviet space scientists have 
not yet received all the money they need for the socalled mars 94 
mission 
we have got funding for instruments but not for the 
spacecraft said albert galeev head of the institute of space 
research in moscow 
he was in pasadena for the second international conference on 
solar system exploration being held at the california institute of 
technology to coincide with voyager 2s close encounter with neptune 
thursday 
he said he expected the remainder of the money to be approved 
soon but the delay has already forced scientists to cut back plans 
for mars 94 galeev said 
the mission had been planned to include a rover that could move 
about the martian surface but because of delays in funding there is 
no longer time to develop and test such a rover by 1994 he said 
the mission had also been planned to include one or more helium 
balloons designed to take measurements as they drift through the 
martian atmosphere and possibly even land to study the martian 
surface at different points 
the most immediate impact on the us mars program would be if 
they decide not to go ahead with the balloon experiment said 
casani 
the mars observer the american mars mission scheduled to be 
launched in 1992 was designed to be able to communicate with the 
balloons he said 
galeev said in an interview that at the meeting of the congress 
of peoples deputies in moscow in late may and early june some 
delegates had argued that money should be diverted from the space 
