<TEXT>
the center for marine conservation accused the 
commerce department on thursday of squelching scientific findings 
and treating the issue of endangered sea turtle deaths as if it were 
a matter of soviet intrigue and espionage 
the agency caught between the opposing demands of shrimpers and 
environmentalists is under a court order to draft final regulations 
by sept 8 that would protect endangered sea turtles from drowning 
in shrimpers nets 
the public was given 15 days to comment and has deluged the 
department with thousands of letters but the center for marine 
conservation says it has been unable to obtain biological opinions 
from the agencys own scientists on the most effective way of 
preventing sea turtle deaths 
at issue is whether shrimpers must be required to equip their 
nets with devices that allow turtles to escape the choice of 
environmentalists or whether they should restrict their tow times 
and check their nets before the submerged turtles drown the choice 
of many gulf coast shrimpers 
under temporary regulations shrimpers are being required to pull 
their nets every 105 minutes or use the turtle excluder devices 
teds 
the center for marine conservation said commerce has 
squelched biological recommendations and ignored the findings of 
its own scientists that teds are far more effective in preventing 
turtle deaths than restricted tow times 
the centers marydele donnelly accused the agency of withholding 
so much information on its scientists own studies that her 
organization has been forced to file freedom of information act 
requests 
conservation of endangered species is not a matter of soviet 
intrigue and espionage she said the american public has a 
right to know how and why commerce secretary robert mosbacher 
came to such outlandish conclusions regarding 105minute tow times 
when the record is clear that these regulations are based on false 
premises 
commerce spokesman brian gorman said every possible credible 
source of information from within and outside the agency is being 
considered as the final rules are drafted 
meanwhile public comment on the issue continues to pour in the 
national marine fisheries service has counted 3100 letters to date 
and more are coming in said charles karnella chief of the 
protected species management division 
he said the letters are overwhelmingly in favor of teds but 
would not provide a tally 
