<TEXT>
japanese piano makers said thursday they will stop 
using imported ivory in piano keys to help protect african elephants 
the musical instrument makers said synthetic materials can 
replace the ivory preferred by many pianists because it absorbs 
perspiration from the fingers 
the measure was taken in the interest of saving elephants 
said haruo gomi a spokesman for yamaha corp japans largest 
musical instrument maker 
shigeru sugiyama spokesman of the kawai musical instruments 
mfg said his company also decided to discontinue imports of ivory 
to make piano keys 
both yamaha and kawai are based in hamamatsu central japan 
gomi said yamaha has used synthetic products to make keys of some 
expensive models for 10 years 
yamaha produces 190000 pianos a year he said and uses about 
1540 pounds of ivory to make 300350 highgrade pianos including 
its topoftheline cf3 grand that costs 44600 
gomi said the company imported about 2 tons of ivory in 1987 
enough to last three years 
in june the japanese government drastically curtailed ivory 
imports to help save african elephants from extinction among 
measures the government banned shipments of worked ivory and ivory 
scraps less than 22 pounds and under 8 inches long 
in 1988 japan imported 106 tons of unprocessed ivory and 26 tons 
of finished ivory according to government figures of the total 53 
percent of the imported ivory was used for family seals that are 
commonly used as a substitute for signatures on documents 28 
percent for jewelry 12 percent for musical instruments and the 
remaining 7 percent for art products according to the private 
conservation group traffic japan 
the african elephant population has fallen from about 15 million 
in 1978 to as few as 400000 today mostly because of poachers who 
seek the valuable tusks 
 
several western nations including the united states have banned 
the import of ivory in recent months the 102nation convention on 
international trade in endangered species will consider a worldwide 
ban on the ivory trade in october 
