indication the roh regime has given up promises for 
democratization 
roh has introduced widespread democratic reforms since he took 
office last year but critics complain he has not done enough to 
introduce full democracy 
the presidents foes also charge that roh is reneging on his 
campaign promise to clear up misdeeds and corruption committed under 
his disgraced predecessor chun doohwan 
prosecutors say they have evidence kim daejung knew about suhs 
trip two months before the case was made public in june he denied 
it saying he learned of the trip shortly before suh turned himself 
in to authorities in late june 
suh a 52yearold farmer elected to the national assembly in 
april 1988 was expelled from the party after his trip was made 
public 
the seoul government prohibits unauthorized travel to north 
korea an enemy country since the korean peninsula was divided in 
1945 the two koreas fought a bloody war in 195053 and never signed 
a peace treaty 
kim daejung 64 spent almost seven years in prison after a 1976 
conviction on antigovernment activity and a 1980 conviction on 
sedition charges opposition supporters say these convictions were 
based on trumpedup charges by repressive governments 
