<TEXT>
drexel burnham lambert inc is reminding its 
employees not to do business with its indicted former junk bond 
chief michael milken 
separately sources said wednesday that federal prosecutors are 
reconsidering their agreement with drexel that bars the investment 
house from paying milken his 1988 compensation of more than 100 
million 
drexel this week issued a threesentence memo to all workers 
saying they cannot advise corporate clients if they also are being 
advised by milken who has resigned from drexel and set up a 
financial consulting firm 
while employees of drexel burnham may have purely social 
contact with them business matters that do or could involve drexel 
burnham are not to be discussed read the memo signed by drexel 
chief executive frederick joseph 
under a separate settlement with the securities and exchange 
commission drexel and its employees are barred from doing business 
with milken and his brother lowell who also is charged by the 
government 
the milkens were not party to the firms sec settlement which is 
to take effect after drexel enters its criminal plea 
drexel spokesman steven anreder said the memo was issued because 
the firm is determined to live within the spirit of the sec 
agreement in the absence of its finalization 
drexel was barred from paying milken as part of its formal 
settlement of criminal securities fraud charges 
the withholding of pay has been controversial because milken has 
not been charged with committing any wrongdoing during 1988 milken 
has challenged the provision in us district court in manhattan 
sources familiar with the case who asked not to be identified 
said prosecutors have not made a final decision on whether to let 
drexel pay milken his compensation which court documents place at 
well over 100 million 
but they indicated a reversal may be made because legal experts 
have criticized the provision as potentially unconstitutional and 
the government may not want to start its case against milken before 
us district judge kimba wood on the wrong foot 
they said ending the lengthy delay of drexels plea in the case 
was not a factor in reconsidering the payment provision but the 
move could help to speed resolution of the drawnout case 
spokesmen for drexel and milken declined to comment 
assistant us attorney john carroll said when and if we make 
a decision with regard to any matters in these cases we will tell 
them to judge wood before we tell them to anyone else 
milken was charged in march in a 98count indictment with 
racketeering and fraud related to securities transactions he 
pleaded innocent and is scheduled to go to trial in march 
a us district court hearing is scheduled for sept 6 on 
milkens arguments that the pay provision deprived him of 
constitutional due process 
the government has indicated milkens compensation was ordered 
withheld on grounds it was improper for drexel to settle criminal 
charges while it was paying millions to the employee allegedly 
responsible for illegal activity 
drexel agreed in december to pay 650 million and plead guilty to 
six felonies for violating securities laws charges that stemmed 
from the ivan boesky insider trading case the plea has been held up 
by a series of legal issues related to milken the last of which was 
his challenge of the pay requirement 
