<TEXT>
implementation of ah robins cos 
reorganization plan will be delayed until at least november while 
claimants who challenged the plan appeal its approval to the us 
supreme court claimants said thursday 
were going to the supreme court said rosemary 
menardsanford one of thousands of women who claimed they were 
injured by the dalkon shield birthcontrol device marketed by the 
company in the early 1970s 
more than 94 percent of the claimants voted in favor of the 
reorganization plan confirmed by us district judge robert r 
merhige jr but about 900 women had rejected the plan which was 
upheld in june by the 4th us circuit court of appeals along with a 
related classaction suit against aetna casualty and surety co 
had no further appeals been sought the trust would have been 
funded and the plan consummated sept 28 robins spokesman roscoe 
puckett said thursday 
robins recognizes that it is the appellants right to seek 
further review of the plan by the supreme court puckett said 
however the company believes that the overwhelming majority of 
dalkon shield claimants who voted to accept the plan will share its 
deep disappointment and frustration that there will be further 
indeterminant delays in implementation of the plan 
the appellants decision which will continue to cost claimants 
roughly half a million dollars daily in lost interest income is 
particularly disappointing in light of the fact that five judges 
already have considered the reorganization plan and judged it 
proper 
robins a large pharmaceutical company based in richmond sought 
protection under chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy laws in august 
1985 
